    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:ff932dfe-8e57-46c5-a147-77fb0dfec8da",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 50-year-old male who presents to the outpatient clinic with a chief complaint of persistent lower back pain radiating into his left buttock over the past six weeks. He is a moderately built man, visibly uncomfortable shifting in his seat, and walks with a slightly guarded, antalgic gait. He winces when asked to bend forward and reports that sitting for prolonged periods significantly worsens his discomfort.\n\n{patientName} works as a mid-level logistics manager at a regional freight company, spending approximately seven to eight hours per day at a desk in front of multiple computer screens. His job involves occasional manual handling of cargo documentation but mostly sedentary office work. He commutes 45 minutes each way by car, which he describes as \"the worst part of the day.\" He lives in a suburban home with his wife of 22 years and their two teenage children.\n\nOutside of work, {patientName} used to enjoy recreational golf and weekend cycling, but both activities have been severely limited by his back pain over the past month. He reports poor sleep quality due to discomfort when rolling over in bed, leading to fatigue and mild irritability. He admits to a sedentary lifestyle overall and acknowledges he has gained approximately 8 kg over the last three years without any formal exercise routine.\n\nHe is a former light smoker who quit 10 years ago and drinks alcohol socially — roughly 3–4 standard drinks per week. His diet consists largely of convenience foods and takeaways during the week, though his wife cooks balanced home meals on weekends. He denies any bowel or bladder dysfunction, fever, or unexplained weight loss. The pain is described as a dull, aching 6/10 at rest, worsening to 8/10 with prolonged standing or lifting.\n\n{patientName} is notably anxious about his condition, fearing it may be something \"serious\" like a tumour or nerve damage. He is cooperative and motivated to understand his diagnosis, and has already tried over-the-counter ibuprofen with partial relief. He has a supportive social network and expresses willingness to engage with physiotherapy if recommended."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:10844dc6-30d5-4bf5-b1c3-768b54634cd7",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has a background history of well-controlled hypertension diagnosed at age 44, for which he is currently on antihypertensive therapy. He was also diagnosed with type 2 hyperlipidaemia at age 47 and is on a statin. He has no known diabetes mellitus, though his last fasting glucose was borderline at 5.9 mmol/L. He has no history of prior spinal surgery, fractures, or significant trauma to the lumbar region. He reports a single prior episode of acute low back pain approximately four years ago that resolved spontaneously within two weeks without formal treatment.\n\n{patientName} has no history of inflammatory arthritis, psoriasis, or inflammatory bowel disease. He has never been hospitalised overnight for any condition and has no surgical history apart from an inguinal hernia repair in his late 30s. He is up to date with routine health checks. He is a non-smoker (ex-smoker, 10 pack-year history, quit at age 40) and consumes alcohol within moderate limits. There is a family history of cardiovascular disease (father) and osteoarthritis (mother). His BMI is currently 28.4 kg/m², placing him in the overweight category. He reports no known drug allergies. Adherence to prescribed medications is described as \"mostly good\" with occasional missed doses."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
